<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900501-0054</DOCNO><DOCID>900501-0054.</DOCID><HL>   Advanced Micro, Unit   Of Samsung Settle   Dispute Over Patents</HL><DATE>05/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   AMD C.SEL CY</CO><IN>SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)</IN><LP>   SUNNYVALE, Calif. -- Advanced Micro Devices Inc. andSamsung Semiconductor Inc. said they settled two-year-oldlitigation over Advanced patents covering semiconductorcircuits.   In its suit, filed in August 1988 in federal court in SanJose, Calif., Advanced said that Samsung infringed on patentscovering its AM22V10 programmable array logic chip, one ofAdvanced Micro's leading products.</LP><TEXT>   As part of the settlement, Samsung Semiconductor, the SanJose, Calif., unit of South Korea-based Samsung, acknowledgedthat the Advanced patents are legally valid and said that intwo years it would stop selling certain products, includingchips protected by the patents.   Advanced said it would receive royalties from theresulting sales, which cover existing Samsung commitments tocustomers, although an Advanced spokesman declined toelaborate on the monetary amount.   The Advanced Micro complaint was a countersuit to anearlier lawsuit filed by Samsung against Advanced Micro, inwhich Samsung was seeking to have the basic patent coveringAdvanced's chip invalidated. Advanced Micro sued three otherconcerns on the same patent-infringement claims.   Those claims remain outstanding against Atmel Corp. andCypress Semiconductor Inc., both of San Jose; and GazelleMicrocircuits Inc., Santa Clara, Calif.   With the settlement of the litigation, the two companiessaid they agreed to discuss possible future businessrelationships in areas of mutual technological interest.   Advanced Micro stock rose 12.5 cents yesterday to close at$8.75 in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.</TEXT></DOC>